Camila Ruiz: Heads-up — the new Astro edge starter used in the eval harness is flaky. Repro below, seems tied to edge fetch + auth-retry behavior.

Camila Ruiz: Local repro: clone examples/astro-edge-starter, pnpm install, start in edge emulation, set REDWOOD_TEST_EXPIRE_MS=900, call /api/stream. Stream truncates mid-response and eval marks it as regression.

Noah Bennett: I can reproduce on macos runner. Log shows: "StreamError: response body closed after 401 mid-read". Happens only in edge emulation, not Node dev.

Priya Singh: likely cause: in edge isolates we can't reliably share global refresh locks. Our JS SDK uses a single-process queue which works in Node but not in multi-isolate edge envs. So a mid-stream 401 causes one isolate to refresh while another keeps using stale token.

Ethan Park: snippet from src/routes/api/stream.ts:```js
export async function GET() {
  const s = await rwClient.chat.stream({ messages });
  return new Response(s, { headers: { 'content-type': 'text/event-stream' } });
}
```

Sofia Alvarez: repro detail: if you call the endpoint twice quickly with REDWOOD_TEST_EXPIRE_MS low, sometimes you get full stream, sometimes truncated. Flaky pattern.

Camila Ruiz: short-term workaround I added to the example: issue an ephemeral token per-request from a serverless function and use that token for the edge fetch. That avoids cross-isolate refresh races. Patch: /api/ephemeral -> returns signed short-lived token.

Noah Bennett: here's minimal ephemeral flow we used in the example:```js
// server -> /api/ephemeral
const t = await controlPlane.issueEphemeral({ ttl: 30 });
return new Response(JSON.stringify({ token: t }));
// edge client then uses Authorization: Bearer <token>
```

Priya Singh: long-term we should either: 1) make the SDK detect edge-like env and surface a clear pattern (ephemeral token helper), or 2) implement resumable streaming where client restarts transparently after refresh. Option 1 is lower friction for starters.

Ethan Park: another gotcha: the example uses Headers object in the fetch call and our telemetry middleware was appending instead of setting headers, causing duplicate header values after a retry which some edge platforms stringify oddly -> 400. Fixed in example by converting to plain object before passing to SDK.

Sofia Alvarez: logs: "Invalid header: x-rw-trace: a,b" in some runners. Repro by forcing 401 + retry.

Camila Ruiz: I opened a PR with three changes: 1) ephemeral-token example + README, 2) client wrapper that restarts stream once if opts.idempotent === true, 3) note in eval harness to run edge emulation job. PR: https://github.com/redwood-inference/examples/pull/314 (WIP).

Noah Bennett: temporary CI unblock: set REDWOOD_SDK_ASSUME_RETRY=true in the example's CI job so streams will restart once on 401. Not ideal but gets parity green while we iterate.

Priya Singh: SDK-side ideas: expose issueEphemeralToken() helper in control-plane SDK for examples, and add an isEdgeInit flag so SDK warns if used in edge without ephemeral flow. Also add a clone-opts-before-queue to avoid middleware mutation races.

Ethan Park: small code suggestion for middleware hygiene:```js
return async (next, opts) => {
  const headers = Object.fromEntries(new Headers(opts.headers || {}));
  headers['x-rw-trace'] = generateTraceId();
  return next({ ...opts, headers });
}
```

Sofia Alvarez: FYI embeddings parity popped once in this starter too — shapes were number[] vs Float32Array. We normalized in the example by calling normalizeEmbeddings(response) before passing into LangChain. Added note in README.

Camila Ruiz: devex-bot recorded CI issue: https://ci.internal.redwood/gh/examples/astro-edge-starter/6 -> tests/eval/streaming-edge -> 2487654365

Noah Bennett: I'll follow up with a small SDK PR to add a docs-only helper for ephemeral tokens and a runtime warning when window-like edge globals are present. PR WIP: https://github.com/redwood-inference/js-sdk/pull/270

Priya Singh: added an eval harness fixture to the example that forces expiry and validates that either the ephemeral flow or single-restart behavior yields a complete stream. This should catch regressions in CI.

Ethan Park: one more caveat — ephemeral tokens for every request increase control-plane ops. We note in README: "ephemeral flow is demo-only; use it for edge starters and testing, not for high-throughput production."

Sofia Alvarez: merged small README + example fixes to main branch in examples repo. Will keep the CI toggle for one week while SDK helper lands.

devex-bot: PR merged: examples#314 by Camila Ruiz at 2487654388 -> epic/edge-starters. :shipit:

Camila Ruiz: thanks all. If anyone finds similar patterns in Vercel edge or Cloudflare, drop findings here and we'll expand ephemeral helper docs.

